<subSubSection pageId="202" pageNumber="480" type="distribution">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6707558" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6707558" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6707558/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="202" pageNumber="480" targetBox="[1459,2051,302,716]" targetPageId="202">
<paragraph blockId="202.[2074,2667,302,721]" pageId="202" pageNumber="480">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2075,2250,495,524]" pageId="202" pageNumber="480">Distribution.</emphasis>
Extreme S Brazil (S Rio Grande do Sul State) and N &amp; E Uruguay.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="202" pageNumber="480" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="202.[2074,2667,302,721]" lastBlockId="202.[1461,2668,732,1155]" pageId="202" pageNumber="480">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2075,2360,570,603]" pageId="202" pageNumber="480">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 92-123 mm, tail 88-97 mm, ear 16-19 mm, hindfoot 23-28 mm; weight 20-61 g. Reig’s Grass Mouse is a moderately large species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1609,1708,732,761]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Akodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="202" pageNumber="480" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Akodon</taxonomicName>
. Dorsum is gray olivaceous; tail is bicolored; and forefeet and hindfeet are covered with grayish hair.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="202" pageNumber="480" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="202.[1461,2668,732,1155]" pageId="202" pageNumber="480">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1463,1574,807,840]" pageId="202" pageNumber="480">Habitat.</emphasis>
Subtropical gallery forests with dense litter, interface of forested habitats and grasslands, and swamp forests.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1463,1963,886,919]" pageId="202" pageNumber="480" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph blockId="202.[1461,2668,732,1155]" box="[1463,1963,886,919]" pageId="202" pageNumber="480">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1463,1724,886,919]" pageId="202" pageNumber="480">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
No information.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1463,2625,925,958]" pageId="202" pageNumber="480" type="breeding">
<paragraph blockId="202.[1461,2668,732,1155]" box="[1463,2625,925,958]" pageId="202" pageNumber="480">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1463,1597,925,958]" pageId="202" pageNumber="480">Breeding.</emphasis>
Breeding of Reig’s Grass Mouse probably occurs from spring to autumn.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1461,2159,969,998]" pageId="202" pageNumber="480" type="activity">
<paragraph blockId="202.[1461,2668,732,1155]" box="[1461,2159,969,998]" pageId="202" pageNumber="480">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1461,1696,969,998]" pageId="202" pageNumber="480">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
Reig’s Grass Mouse is nocturnal.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1463,2402,1003,1036]" pageId="202" pageNumber="480" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="202.[1461,2668,732,1155]" box="[1463,2402,1003,1036]" pageId="202" pageNumber="480">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1463,2163,1003,1036]" pageId="202" pageNumber="480">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
No information.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1464,2514,1043,1076]" pageId="202" pageNumber="480" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="202.[1461,2668,732,1155]" box="[1464,2514,1043,1076]" pageId="202" pageNumber="480">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1464,1812,1043,1076]" pageId="202" pageNumber="480">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
